doc.ContractDescription: BACKGROUND FUTURE CONCEPTS FOR ULTRAEFFICIENT AIR TRAFFIC OPERATIONS RELY UPON PRECISE CONTIOL AND OPTIMIZATION OF OPERATIONS. HOWEVER, THE CURRENT QUALITY OF OPERATIONAL DATA, PREDICTABILITY OF WEATHER AND NATIONAL AIRSPACE SYSTEM NAS BEHAVIOR, AND COMPUTATIONAL RESOURCES ARE INSUFFICIENT TO SUPPORT ADVANCED CONCEPTS. AS A RESULT, CONCEPTS OFTEN FAIL UNDER COMMON OPERATIONAL CIRCUMSTANCES. THERE AIE TWO CONSEQUENCES TO SUCH FAILURES BENEFITS ARE NOT REALIZED AS OPERATIONS REVERT TO LESS EFFICIENT, MORE IOBUST DEFAULTS AND THE COST OF FAILURE INCREASES AS THE GAP BETWEEN DEMAND BASED ON UNREALIZABLE PERFORMANCE EXPECTATIONS AND THE REALITY OF ROBUST OPERATIONS WIDENS. AS INCREASING AMOUNTS OF OPERATIONAL DATA BIG DATA AND COMPUTATIONAL POWER BECOME AVAILABLE, OPPORTUNITIES ARISE TO CREATE EFFICIENT, ROBUST OPERATING PARADIGMS WHICH WILL LEAD TO MAJOR PERFORMANCE IMPROVEMENTS, INCLUDING INCREASED CAPACITY AND REDUCED DELAY, FUEL AND ENVIRONMENTAL IMPACTS. OBJECTIVES THE OBJECTIVE OF THE PROPOSED WORK IS TO IDENTIFY INEFFICIENCIES IN THE NAS DUE TO LACK OF ACCESS TO DATA AND COMPUTATIONAL RESOURCES. DEVELOP A FRAMEWORK AND REFERENCE IMPLEMENTATION FOR EXPLOITATION OF AVIATION-FOCUSED BIG DATA TO IMPROVE AND MEASURE NAS PERFORMANCE. DEMONSTRATE FRAMEWORK UHUTY THROUGH CASE STUDIES WHICH INCLUDE PROOF-OF-CONCEPT PROTOTYPING, EVALUATION, AND BENEFITS ANALYSIS TO GUIDE FURTHER DEVELOPMENT. PHASE 2 WILL INCLUDE EXTENSIONS TO INCORPORATE DATA FROM SIMULATIONS OF FUTURE CONCEPTS FOR FLIGHT MANAGEMENT LIFECYCLE, UNMANNED FLIGHT, ETC. DESIGN OF INTERFACES BETWEEN THE BIG DATA FRAMEWORK AND NASAS SHADOW MODE ASSESSMENT USING REALISTIC TECHNOLOGIES FOR THE NAS (SMART-NAS). DEVELOPMENT OF REAL-TIME OPERATIONAL PROTOTYPES BASED ON THE REFERENCE IMPLEMENTATION.

doc.ContractDescription: OUR SCIENTIFIC GOAL, INSPIRED BY MAVEN SCIENCE QUESTION #1, IS TO INTEGRATE MAVEN DATA FROM MULTIPLE INSTRUMENTS TO DETERMINE HOW THE STATE OF THE DAYSIDE IONOSPHERE IS INFLUENCED BY THE NEUTRAL ATMOSPHERE, SOLAR FLUX, AND MAGNETIC ENVIRONMENT. THE PRIMARY WAY BY WHICH WE SHALL ADDRESS THIS GOAL IS TO TEST SIMPLE IONOSPHERIC PREDICTIONS IN THE TOPSIDE AND AT THE MAIN PEAK USING MAVEN DATA, ACCOMPANIED BY INTERPRETATION WITH THE BOSTON UNIVERSITY MARS IONOSPHERIC MODEL. THIS IS A NATURAL EXTENSION OF OUR CURRENT RESEARCH USING EXISTING DATASETS. ALMOST ALL NECESSARY DATA ARE INCLUDED IN THE MAVEN KEY PARAMETER FILES THAT DISSEMINATE USEABLE DATA AROUND THE MAVEN TEAM RAPIDLY AND REGULARLY. OUR WORK IS DIVIDED INTO FIVE TASKS, EACH OF WHICH ALSO DIRECTLY SUPPORTS MISSION OPERATIONS AND DECISION-MAKING. TASK A EXAMINES THE VERTICAL STRUCTURE OF THE TOPSIDE IONOSPHERE. TASK B EXAMINES THE COMPOSITION OF THE TOPSIDE IONOSPHERE. TASK C EXAMINES THE PEAK ELECTRON DENSITY. TASK D EXAMINES THE NEUTRAL PRESSURE AT THE IONOSPHERIC PEAK. TASK E, WHICH IS STRONGLY LINKED TO MISSION OPERATIONS, WILL SUPPORT SPACECRAFT OPERATIONS INSIDE THE ATMOSPHERE.
